answer.\n\nText:\n----Reports-----\nid,full_content\r\n13,\"# AI Policy and Academic Publishing Stakeholders\n\nThe community centers around AI POLICY, which governs the ethical, transparent, and responsible use of artificial intelligence in academic publishing. Key entities include AUTHORS, EDITORS, PEER REVIEWERS, PUBLISHERS, and organizations like Elsevier, Taylor & Francis, and MIT Press. These entities are interconnected through relationships emphasizing transparency, authorship, compliance, and ethical use of AI. The policies set by AI POLICY influence how authors disclose AI usage, how editors enforce guidelines, and how publishers manage the publication process.\n\n## AI POLICY as a central governing framework\n\nAI POLICY serves as the central governing framework for the ethical and responsible use of AI in academic publishing. It is developed by major publishers such as Elsevier, Taylor & Francis, and Springer Nature, and it addresses content creation, peer review, and editorial decision-making. This policy ensures that AI technologies are used in a manner that upholds academic integrity, accountability, and ethical standards. [records: Entities (26), Relationships (357, 358, 368, 372)]\n\n## Authorship guidelines and AI tool restrictions\n\nAuthorship guidelines clearly state that AI tools cannot be listed as authors or co-authors due to their inability to assume ethical, legal, or scientific responsibility. This principle is consistently emphasized across multiple descriptions, including those from BMJ, Elsevier, and De Gruyter Brill. Authors must disclose the use of AI tools in their work, ensuring transparency and maintaining the integrity of scholarly output. [records: Entities (17, 29), Relationships (130, 293, 294, 296)]\n\n## Transparency as a core requirement\n\nTransparency is a fundamental requirement in academic publishing, mandating that authors disclose the use of AI tools in manuscripts, particularly in sections like Materials and Methods. Publishers such as BMJ, Taylor & Francis, and Wiley have incorporated these requirements into their policies, ensuring that the role of AI in research is clearly communicated. Transparency also extends to the peer review process, where the use of AI tools must be made explicit to maintain accountability. [records: Entities (13, 29), Relationships (114, 244, 248, 252)]\n\n## Compliance with AI policies\n\nCompliance with AI policies is essential for maintaining trust, ensuring legal conformity, and upholding ethical responsibilities associated with AI integration in scholarly communication. This includes adherence to data protection laws, intellectual property rights, and the responsible and transparent use of AI. Publishers such as Emerald and Elsevier emphasize compliance, requiring authors and reviewers to verify that the integration of AI technology aligns with established regulatory frameworks. [records: Entities (24, 29), Relationships (111, 347, 351, 354)]\n\n## Publishers' role in enforcing AI policies\n\nPublishers play a critical role in enforcing AI policies, ensuring that all aspects of the publication process adhere to established ethical and legal standards. They are responsible for overseeing the responsible integration and application of AI tools, thereby maintaining the integrity and credibility of scholarly output. For example, Elsevier's AI policy outlines specific guidelines for handling manuscripts involving AI, while MIT Press prohibits the use of AI tools as authors. [records: Entities (37, 29), Relationships (357, 358, 372, 446)]\n\n## Ethical use of AI in academic publishing\n\nThe ethical use of AI is a central focus of AI policies, emphasizing transparency, accountability, and compliance with academic integrity and privacy principles. Publishers such as Elsevier and Emerald integrate ethical use into their AI policies, highlighting responsibility, accountability, and alignment with principles of privacy, confidentiality, and regulatory compliance. This ensures that AI technologies are used responsibly in research and publication processes. [records: Entities (29, 26), Relationships (253, 264, 365, 366)]\n\n## Peer reviewers' responsibility in AI governance\n\nPeer reviewers are required to follow AI policies as part of their responsibilities, aligning their practices with broader institutional commitments to responsible AI use in academic publishing. Elsevier's AI policy provides instructions for peer reviewers on the ethical use of AI technologies during the review process, emphasizing the importance of adhering to established guidelines to ensure ethical and transparent evaluation of academic submissions. [records: Entities (29, 26), Relationships (188, 179, 183)]\n\n## Editorial decisions and AI\n\nEditorial decisions must be made exclusively by humans, as per AI policies, ensuring that AI does not play a role in the decision-making process. This policy, specifically outlined in Elsevier's framework, emphasizes human agency and responsibility in editorial functions. The interplay between these two entities highlights a structured approach to maintaining control over editorial outcomes in the context of AI integration. [records: Entities (29, 26), Relationships (305, 369, 304)]\n\n## Disclosure of AI usage in manuscripts\n\nDisclosures of AI usage are required in manuscripts to ensure clarity and accountability throughout the research and publication process. AI policies mandate detailed disclosures about the use of AI technologies, including Generative AI tools, to ensure that readers understand the role of AI in scholarly outputs. This requirement is designed to uphold academic integrity and provide transparency regarding the use of AI in research. [records: Entities (29, 26), Relationships (31, 316, 241, 294)]\n\n## Rights protection and AI\n\nRights protection is a key aspect of AI policies, ensuring that authors and publishers are not subjected to unintended rights transfers when utilizing AI tools or generating content with AI technologies. These policies aim to safeguard intellectual property rights and maintain control over the use of AI-generated content. The overarching goal is to provide clear protections and guidelines that support the interests of both authors and publishers in an evolving AI-driven publishing landscape. [records: Entities (29, 26), Relationships (331, 332, 340)]\"\r\n16,\"# Emerald, AI Policies, and Academic Publishing Stakeholders\n\nThe community centers around Emerald, an academic publisher with comprehensive AI policies, and includes key stakeholders such as authors, editors, peer reviewers, and organizations like ICMJE, ISPOR, and IEEE. These entities are interconnected through relationships that emphasize accountability, transparency, data privacy, and human oversight in the use of AI tools within academic publishing. The policies set by publishers and organizations guide the ethical and responsible integration of AI, ensuring research integrity and compliance with legal and ethical standards.\n\n## Emerald's role as a leading academic publisher with AI policies\n\nEmerald is a central entity in this community, having developed a comprehensive AI policy to govern the use of AI tools in academic publishing. This policy emphasizes ethical standards, transparency, and human oversight, reflecting Emerald's commitment to maintaining integrity in scholarly communication. Emerald's policies require authors to disclose AI usage, ensure originality, and maintain data privacy, while also restricting the use of generative AI in peer review processes. [records: Entities (81), Relationships (368, 435, 397, 256, 240, 318, 410, 456)]\n\n## Accountability as a core principle in AI governance\n\nAccountability is a fundamental concept in this community, involving authors, publishers, editors, and peer reviewers. Authors are held responsible for the accuracy, originality, and ethical use of AI-generated content, while publishers like Emerald enforce policies to ensure compliance. Editors and peer reviewers are accountable for upholding editorial standards and ensuring that AI tools do not compromise research integrity. This shared responsibility underscores the need for structured oversight and clear guidelines in the integration of AI into academic publishing. [records: Entities (27), Relationships (129, 172, 195, 246, 296, 373, 375, 376)]\n\n## Data privacy and compliance with legal standards\n\nData privacy is a critical concern in the use of AI tools within academic publishing. Publishers like Emerald and Johns Hopkins University Press ensure compliance with data protection laws when using AI technologies, particularly when handling personally identifiable information. Authors must also check AI tool terms to ensure they protect data privacy and confidentiality. This emphasis on data privacy reflects broader efforts to safeguard sensitive information and maintain trust in the research process. [records: Entities (64), Relationships (123, 58, 457, 452)]\n\n## Transparency and disclosure requirements\n\nTransparency is a key element of AI governance in academic publishing. Policies require authors to disclose the use of AI tools in their submissions, including specific citations for AI-generated content. This ensures that readers and reviewers can assess the role of AI in the research and verify its accuracy. Emerald, for example, mandates transparency in AI usage to maintain trust and integrity in scholarly work. Similar requirements are enforced by other publishers and organizations, reinforcing the importance of openness in AI-assisted research. [records: Entities (24), Relationships (321, 243, 318, 246, 374)]\n\n## Human oversight as a safeguard against bias and errors\n\nHuman oversight is essential to ensure the ethical and responsible use of AI tools in academic publishing. Policies mandate that AI systems are subject to human review to prevent algorithmic bias, inaccuracies, and ethical violations. Emerald, for instance, requires human oversight in the peer review process to maintain quality and fairness. Organizations like ICMJE and IEEE also emphasize the importance of human judgment in evaluating AI-assisted research, highlighting the need for a balanced approach that combines technological innovation with human expertise. [records: Entities (104), Relationships (397, 439, 263, 245, 397, 439)]\n\n## Collaboration between publishers and organizations\n\nPublishers such as Emerald, Springer Nature, Wiley, and SAGE collaborate with organizations like ICMJE, ISPOR, and IEEE to develop and enforce AI policies. These collaborations help establish consistent guidelines for the ethical use of AI across different academic fields. For example, ISPOR has developed policies to ensure the responsible use of AI in health economics research, while ICMJE provides guidelines for authors regarding AI-assisted technologies. Such partnerships reflect a growing consensus among stakeholders to address the challenges posed by AI in scholarly communication. [records: Entities (109, 115, 105, 106, 114, 108), Relationships (445, 448, 437, 444, 447, 446)]\n\n## Ethical use of AI tools and prevention of misuse\n\nThe ethical use of AI tools is a central focus of the policies outlined in the text. Publishers and organizations emphasize that AI should be used responsibly to support, not replace, human creativity and judgment. For instance, SAGE prohibits the use of AI tools as authors and requires transparency in their use, while Johns Hopkins University Press enforces ethical standards in AI application. These measures aim to prevent the misuse of AI, such as plagiarism or manipulation of research data, and ensure that AI enhances rather than undermines the integrity of academic work. [records: Entities (27, 64, 105, 115), Relationships (258, 295, 376, 410, 446, 448)]\n\n## AI detection software as a tool for enforcement\n\nAI detection software plays a crucial role in enforcing AI policies by identifying machine-generated content and ensuring compliance with ethical standards. ISPOR, for example, uses AI detection software to monitor the use of AI tools in its journals and events. This technology helps publishers detect potential misuse of AI and maintain the credibility of published research. The use of AI detection software reflects a proactive approach to AI governance, supporting transparency and accountability in academic publishing. [records: Entities (114), Relationships (447, 463)]\n\n## Authorship and the exclusion of AI from authorship roles\n\nAuthorship policies clearly state that AI tools cannot be listed as authors, reinforcing the principle of human accountability in academic publishing. ICMJE, for instance, emphasizes that authors are fully responsible for their work, including any content generated with the assistance of AI tools. This policy ensures that human agency remains central to the research and publication process, preventing the misattribution of credit and maintaining the integrity of scholarly output. [records: Entities (106, 114), Relationships (296, 373, 375)]\n\n## Compliance with AI policies as a legal and ethical imperative\n\nCompliance with AI policies is a legal and ethical requirement in academic publishing. Policies mandate adherence to transparency, accountability, and data privacy standards, ensuring that AI tools are used responsibly. Publishers like Emerald and Springer Nature have established comprehensive policies to regulate AI use, while organizations like COPE provide guidance to support these efforts. Compliance mechanisms are essential for maintaining trust in the academic publishing ecosystem and aligning technological advancements with established ethical and legal frameworks. [records: Entities (61, 109, 115, 105, 106, 108), Relationships (355, 353, 390, 449, 378, 432)]\"\r\n\n\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\r\n14,ETHICAL USE,\"The concept of \"\"ETHICAL USE\"\" refers to the responsible and appropriate application of AI technologies, including AI tools and Generative AI, across various stages of academic research, manuscript preparation, and publishing. This framework emphasizes adherence to principles of privacy, confidentiality, and compliance, ensuring that AI is used in a manner that upholds academic integrity, transparency, and research ethics. It applies to authors, editors, and reviewers, with a focus on preventing the replacement of human judgment and creativity by AI systems. The ethical use of AI in academic publishing also involves ensuring accuracy, avoiding plagiarism or fabrication, and maintaining compliance with publication standards, copyright regulations, and integrity guidelines. Additionally, it requires proper citation and disclosure when AI tools are employed in academic writing, reinforcing accountability and trust within the scholarly community.\",31\r\n123,TAYLOR & FRANCIS,\"Taylor & Francis is a prominent publisher of academic journals and books that actively promotes the responsible use of Generative AI tools within the academic publishing landscape. The organization emphasizes the importance of maintaining integrity, transparency, and ethical standards in its publishing processes. Additionally, Taylor & Francis provides guidance on the application of Generative AI tools, reflecting its commitment to shaping the future of academic publishing in an informed and responsible manner. As a key player in the academic publishing ecosystem, Taylor & Francis plays a significant role in addressing the challenges and opportunities presented by AI technologies.\",14\r\n100,AI-GENERATED CONTENT,\"Content created by AI tools that is presented as original research data or results, which must be disclosed and cited appropriately\"\"\",5\r\n133,FIGURE,\"A visual representation, such as a graph, diagram, or data table, that may be generated or altered using Generative AI\"\"\",3\r\n47,RESEARCH,\"The entity \"\"RESEARCH\"\" refers to the systematic investigation into a subject or topic aimed at discovering new knowledge, establishing facts, and reaching new conclusions. This process may involve the use of AI tools, though it is emphasized that originality and integrity must be maintained throughout. The descriptions highlight that while AI technologies can be part of the research process, they are not always required, and the core focus remains on the pursuit of new understanding through rigorous inquiry. The integration of AI tools is acknowledged as a potential component, but the ethical and methodological standards of research are prioritized.\",3\r\n135,WILEY,\"WILEY is a publisher of academic journals that is committed to ethical publishing, integrity, and transparency in the use of AI technologies. It also sets guidelines for the ethical use of AI in manuscript preparation and publication, reflecting its broader commitment to responsible AI integration within the academic publishing ecosystem.\",6\r\n60,ELSEVIER,\"Elsevier is a major publisher of academic journals and a leader in the field of academic publishing, with a strong commitment to maintaining integrity and ethical standards in the use of AI technologies. The company has integrated AI technologies into its publication processes and has developed specific policies regarding the use of generative AI and large language models (LLMs) in manuscript preparation. These initiatives reflect Elsevier's broader engagement with AI governance and its role in shaping responsible AI practices within the academic publishing ecosystem.\",5\r\n102,ENVIRONMENTAL RAMIFICATIONS,\"The impact of AI tools on the environment, which publishers like Emerald consider when implementing AI policies\"\"\",2\r\n103,SOCIAL RAMIFICATIONS,\"The societal effects of AI tools, including potential inequities and ethical concerns, which publishers aim to address\"\"\",2\r\n101,STRUCTURAL BIASES,\"Potential biases embedded in AI systems that may affect the fairness and accuracy of research outputs, requiring mitigation by publishers\"\"\",2\r\n\n\n-----Claims-----\nhuman_readable_id,subject_id,type,status,description\r\n42,TAYLOR & FRANCIS,RESPONSIBLE USE POLICY,TRUE,\"Taylor & Francis supports the responsible use of Generative AI tools that respect high standards of data security, confidentiality, and copyright protection\"\r\n43,TAYLOR & FRANCIS,AUTHORSHIP RESPONSIBILITIES,TRUE,\"Authors must clearly acknowledge within the article or book any use of Generative AI tools through a statement which includes: the full name of the tool used (with version number), how it was used, and the reason for use\"\r\n44,TAYLOR & FRANCIS,PROHIBITED USE OF GENERATIVE AI,TRUE,\"Generative AI tools must not be listed as an author, because such tools are unable to assume responsibility for the submitted content or manage copyright and licensing agreements\"\r\n45,TAYLOR & FRANCIS,INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY RISKS,TRUE,\"Taylor & Francis currently does not permit the use of Generative AI in the creation and manipulation of images and figures, or original research data for use in our publications\"\r\n46,TAYLOR & FRANCIS,CONFIDENTIALITY RISKS,TRUE,\"Editors must not upload unpublished manuscripts, including any associated files, images or information into Generative AI tools\"\r\n47,TAYLOR & FRANCIS,RESEARCH ETHICS GUIDELINES,TRUE,Research ethics guidelines are still being updated regarding current Generative AI technologies\r\n48,TAYLOR & FRANCIS,AUTHOR ACCOUNTABILITY,TRUE,\"Authors are accountable for the originality, validity, and integrity of the content of their submissions\"\r\n49,TAYLOR & FRANCIS,PROHIBITED USE CASES,TRUE,Authors should not submit manuscripts where Generative AI tools have been used in ways that replace core researcher and author responsibilities\r\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\r\n112,AUTHOR,ETHICAL USE,\"Authors are responsible for the ethical use of AI tech